702570f-a.text:
16th Ave., east side, between 84th and 85th Streets. A view of the Old Cemetery of the New Utrecht Dutch Reformed Church. In the background is seen the St. John's German Evang. Church. This church is on the site of the Old New Utrecht Dutch Reformed Church. The New Utrecht Dutch Reformed Church, moved eastward several blocks.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

702859f-a.text:
(1)
84th Street, north side, east of Sixteenth Ave., showing J. Lott Nostrand house, built about 1670. During the Revolution it became the William Barrie Tavern, at which George Washington is said to have stopped in 1790. Judge John Lott Nostrand was born here in 1856 and lived here until 1902. It was demolished in 1914, to make way for the widening of 84th Street.
About 1900.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)
The same, showing the N.E. corner after the demolition of the house.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

702861f-a.text:
(1)
84th Street, east of Sixteenth Ave; showing St. Johns German Evangelical Church.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(2)
The same; showing a memorial marker in the cemetery near the Church. This commemorates the house in which General Woodhull died in 1775. The house was erected in 1657, Rutgert Joosten Van Brunt purchased it in 1674. It was demolished in 1836, the last occupant, Barent Wyckoff, having inherited it from Rutgert W. Van Brunt. A Photograph of a drawing has been sent to Room 308, the Print Room.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
